As the 2022 Annual Meetings of the African Develop­ment Bank Group (AfDB) starts today in Ac­cra, Ghana, the President of the bank, Dr. Akinwumi Adesina, has reiterated that the bank will contin­ue to maintain an excellent and robust management and governance system. Adesina disclosed this in a statement on his verified Twitter handle @akin_adesi­na . He said the bank will con­tinue to “deliver great value for our clients in Africa”. This year’s meetings mark a return to in-person sessions following virtual meetings over the last two years. -Advertisement- AfDB, together with Glob­al Center on Adaptation, with former UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon are mobilizing $25 billion in support of Afri­ca and with the support of President Emmanuel Macron and G-7, its Affirmative Action for Women in Africa (AFAWA) is also raising $5 billion for women businesses. In 2021, AfDB paid out $483 million to financial institu­tions to lend to women busi­nesses while it will lend $500 million for women in 2022. Adesina said, “The Af­rican Development Bank (AfDB) was ranked by Global Finance as the best multilat­eral financial institution in the world in 2021 while the African Development Fund was ranked by CGD as sec­ond best in the world, ahead of all 28 concessional financ­ing institutions in developed countries. “We are a AAA-rated fi­nancial institution, the only one in Africa. We have con­sistently maintained our stellar AAA credit ratings by all major global credit rating agencies, who consistently praise our excellent risk man­agement at the bank”. POLL He added that over the past six years, through the bank’s High 5 programs, the bank has impacted on 335 million people.